\begin_layout Subsection
Invalid
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vb Z$
\end_inset

 does belong as a predictor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vb y$
\end_inset

, but we assume it is not, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vb Z$
\end_inset

 is an invalid instrument.
 If we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\vb Z$
\end_inset

 as an instrument to generate a predicted value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vb X$
\end_inset

, the predictor 
\begin_inset Formula $\vb{\breve{X}=\hat{X}=Z\hat{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 is not helpful.
 If we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with that, then we are inserting something that is correlated with the
 error term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jargon: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exclusion restriction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: making the IV model work requires the assumption–on a theoretical level–that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vb Z$
\end_inset

 does not belong in the regression prediction of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Weak
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the instrument 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is not highly predictive of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then the final estimates with have high standard errors.
 Even if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 truly does influence 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, the model does not help us see the effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You'll find some caution about IV (or 2SLS) giving biased estimates in the
 literature.
 As Hahn and Hausman point out on many occasions, the bias is not worse
 than OLS.
 In fact, as the instrument becomes weaker, the 2SLS estimate moves away
 from the correct value toward the value that OLS gave.
 As a result, there is no good reason to prefer OLS (it seems to me, anyway).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Hahn and Hausman (2003), they consider a weak instrument with 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}=0.01$
\end_inset

, a very weak instrument, and show that the final estimates of the standard
 errors are distorted.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

As either the number of instrument grows or the covariance between the structura
l and reduced-term stochastic disturbances be- comes large, the downward
 bias in the estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\varepsilon\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

will become large.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (p.
 121).
 As Hahn and Hausman observed elsewhere, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The estimated standard errors for the 2SLS estimator are downward biased,
 sometimes leading to the mistaken inference that the 2SLS estimates are
 much more precise than they actually are.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (2005, p.
 37)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the instrument is invalid–even slightly correlated with the error term–the
 damage from weak instruments is more dramatic.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Thus, when the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is small (e.g., 0.01), a large amount of bias results which does not decrease
 with increasing sample size
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (p.
 123).
\end_layout

