\begin_layout Standard
Greene (2008, p.
 320) presents a regression model for wages that depends on personal characteris
tics as well as weeks worked:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ln\,Wage_{it}=\beta_{1}+\ldots+\beta_{4}Wks_{it}+\beta_{5}Occ_{it}+\ldots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He then observes that one should not estimate that model, because the variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $Wks_{it}$
\end_inset

 is probably jointly determined with the wage.
 That is to say, 
\begin_inset Formula $Wks$
\end_inset

 should go up when 
\begin_inset Formula $ln\,Wage$
\end_inset

 goes up, and as wages go down, then people will work fewer weeks.
 He suggests there should be a second equation for weeks worked
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Wks_{it}=\gamma_{1}+\gamma_{2}lnWage_{it}+\gamma_{3}Ed_{i}+\gamma_{4}Union_{it}+\gamma_{5}Fem_{i}+u_{it}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Wks$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $lnWage$
\end_inset

 are jointly determined, we need instruments for 
\begin_inset Formula $lnWage$
\end_inset

 here, and Greene compares 2 selections of instruments.
 Here's a picture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
